It is the smallest cemetery in Paris. This site adjoins the Saint-Pierre de Montmartre church. It is only open once a year. The public can then only access it on All Saints’ Day. This is how the collection of eighty-five tombs rests the rest of the year.

Execrable welcome from the guard who prevented his own Montmartres from entering this magnificent place, under the pretext that we had a small foldable scooter in our hand. My daughter is 3 years old. Even having the scooter at the entrance seemed impossible??? Too bad to come across this type of individual who is a little too zealous

The smallest and oldest cemetery in Paris is only open on November 1st. It was undoubtedly already a cemetery during the Merovingian period, then in 1688 it belonged to the Benedictine abbey. It was also a parish cemetery before the cemetery was closed during the times of revolution and only occupied again in 1802. The heavy bronze doors here and on the church were created in 1980 by Tommaso Gismondi, who also designed the altar in 2005.
Open only as part of Heritage Days, the latter really offers nothing interesting to discover except that old Montmartre families rest there with the feeling that it is practically abandonment.
